@page "/faq"
@layout Layout.BaseLayout

<div class="faq-container">
    <div class="faq-header">
        <h2>FAQ</h2>
        <p>Quick answers for creating, finding, and editing canvases in Linteum.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-grid">
        <section class="faq-section">
            <h4>What is this project?</h4>
            <p>
                Linteum is a shared pixel canvas app. You can create canvases, subscribe to ones you already know about,
                and place or update pixels together in real time.
            </p>
            <p>
                Subscribed canvases show up in the left sidebar, so keeping your active ones subscribed makes them easy to reach.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="faq-section">
            <h4>How do I create a Canvas?</h4>
            <p>
                Open <strong>Add new canvas</strong> in the sidebar, then enter a name, width, and height.
                You can add a password too if you want to lock it down.
            </p>
            <p>
                Once it’s created, it gets added to your subscriptions and shows up in the sidebar.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="faq-section">
            <h4>How do I subscribe to an existing Canvas?</h4>
            <p>
                Use <strong>Subscribe to canvas</strong> in the sidebar, enter the canvas name, and add a password only if it’s protected.
            </p>
            <p>
                As a quick test, you can try the <strong>VanGogh</strong> canvas.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="faq-section">
            <h4>How does pixel changing work?</h4>
            <p>
                Open a subscribed canvas, pick a color, and place a pixel on the grid.
                <strong>Normal</strong> canvases only allow single-pixel changes, and each user gets up to
                <strong>100 successful changes per day on each canvas</strong>. The pixel manager shows what you have left.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="faq-section">
            <h4>Normal mode</h4>
            <p>
                <strong>Normal</strong> is the standard pixel-by-pixel mode. It’s the one to use when you want a
                per-canvas daily limit of <strong>100 successful pixel changes</strong>.
            </p>
            <p>
                It works well for organized builds, careful fixes, and anything you want to keep controlled.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="faq-section">
            <h4>Economy mode</h4>
            <p>
                <strong>Economy</strong> turns each pixel into a bid. To change one, you need to bid at least one gold more than the current price.
            </p>
            <p>
                If your bid wins, the gold is spent and you become the owner. Stay subscribed and you’ll also get hourly income on the hour.
            </p>
            <p>
                The payout is <strong>floor(10 * (1 + log2(1 + ownedPixelsInCanvas)))</strong>, where
                <strong>ownedPixelsInCanvas</strong> is how many pixels you own in that canvas.
                Even with zero owned pixels, you still get 10 gold per hour as a subscriber.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="faq-section">
            <h4>FreeDraw mode</h4>
            <p>
                <strong>FreeDraw</strong> keeps things open. You can sketch together, plan something out, or just use it for a quick shared draw.
            </p>
            <p>
                It also supports brush-style drawing and text placement from the selected pixel.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="faq-section faq-wide">
            <h4>Source code &amp; Contact</h4>
            <p>
                The source code is on GitHub:
                <a href="https://github.com/DAnikeyev/Linteum" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">https://github.com/DAnikeyev/Linteum</a>
            </p>
            <p>
                For questions or issues, reach out here:
                <a href="mailto:dmitry.anikeyev@gmail.com">dmitry.anikeyev@gmail.com</a>
            </p>
        </section>
    </div>
</div>
